Normalizing the features

Having a brief look at our dataframe and we notice that the features are on different scales (ie. some features have larger values than others) and this may result in features with larger values over-powering those with smaller values (they might end up having a larger impact on the dependent variable). In order to level out or ensure that each feature contributes proportionally to the dependent variable, the features must be normalized (transformed in such a way that the values are on a similar scale).

\[ x_{norm} = \frac{x-\bar{x}}{\sqrt{\sigma}} \]

scale_process = na_process[-9] %>% scale()

scale_df = scale_process %>% as.data.frame()

scale_df$IsDefaulted = na_process$IsDefaulted

scale_df = scale_df[-c(11,14)] # remove transactionyear and issueyear

scale_df %>% head() # the training data

Logistic Regression

Logistic regression models situations like this: Pr[default = yes|balance] (the probability that individual i defaults on their credit payments given their monthly balance, as an example).

What makes logistic regression different from multiple regression is the range of values that the target variable can take on. In our situation the target variable is a probability which ranges from 0 to 1 (the assumption of the distribution can be a bernoulli distribution); in other situations where the target variable is a real number which ranges from -\(\infty\) to \(\infty\) (the assumption of the distribution can be a normal distribution). But OLS regression provides a very convenient framework for variable estimation, confidence intervals and hypothesis tests.

Therefore we must somehow transform our target variable that ranges between 0 and 1 and make it range between -\(\infty\) and \(\infty\):

\[ log(\frac{P(X)}{1-P(X)}) = \beta_{0} + \beta_{1}x \]

# Logistic Regression
glm_train = glm(IsDefaulted ~ ., data = train_input, family = binomial)

Linear Discrimination Analysis

This alternative classification approach has more of a Bayesian feel to it in that it involves finding a reliable estimate of a posterior probability function. We are still interested in Pr[Y = k|X = x] (given that we know a bunch of covariates about an individual denoted as X, what is the probability that they default on credit payments denoted as Y):

Firstly a prior probability must be calculated which will be denoted as \(\pi_{k}\) (which essentially quantifies our initial expectation of an individual defaulting and an individual not defaulting). Secondly a likelihood function must also be defined which says, given that a customer has defaulted what is the probability that customer had this particular set of covariates:

\[ f_{k} (x) = Pr[X|Y = k] \]

Certain assumption need to be made in order for us to estimate \(f_{k} (x)\) (the most common assumption is that the covariates come from a multivariate gaussian which would make \(f_{k} (x)\) a multivariate normal function). Then the posterior probability ends up looking something like this:

\[ Pr[Y = k| X = x] = \frac{\pi_{k} f_{k}(x)}{\sum_{l = 1}^{k} \pi_{l} f_{l} (x)} \]

Naive Bayes

Naive bayes method shares similarities with the LDA method, in that the expression for the posterior probability is the same:

\[ Pr[Y=k|X=x] = \frac{\pi_{k}\mathbf{x}f_{k1}(x_{1})\mathbf{x}f_{k2}(x_{2})\mathbf{x}......\mathbf{x}f_{kp}(x_{p})}{\sum_{l=1}^{k} \pi_{l}\mathbf{x}f_{l1}(x_{1})\mathbf{x}f_{l2}(x_{2})\mathbf{x}.....\mathbf{x}f_{lp}(x_{p})} \]

Instead naive bayes makes the assumption that within the \(k^{th}\) class, the p predictors/covariates are independent. where:

\(f_{kn}\) represents the likelihood function for the \(k^{th}\) class/outcome and the \(n^{th}\) predictor

\(\pi_{l}\) represents the prior probability for the \(l^{th}\) class/outcome

Out from naive bayes:

Generalized-Additive-Models/GAMS

Recall a logisitic regression:

\[ log(\frac{P(X)}{1-P(X)}) = \beta_{0} + \beta_{1}X_{1}+ \beta_{2}X_{2}+....+\beta_{p}X_{p} \] It can be extended to allow for non-linear relationships between each predictor and the target variable by substituting a non-linear function \(f_{j}(x_{ij})\) for the linear function \(x_{ij}\):

\[ log(\frac{P(X)}{1-P(X)}) = \beta_{0} + f_{1}(X_{1}) + f_{2}(X_{2})+....+f_{p}(X_{p})) \]

library(akima)
library(gam)
